Syrus is confounded by this discovery, which will prevent his getting any money from Menedemus on the pretext of redeeming her. After some thought he hits upon two ways in which he can get the money which Clitipho wants to pay Bacchis with. (1) If Chremes will only consent to pretend to affiance Antiphila (the new-found daughter) to Clinia, Clinia’s father will of course give money for necessary expenses. This Chremes, imagining Clinia to be engaged with Bacchis, refuses. (2) To maintain the story of the ransom asked for Antiphila by Bacchis, who had had her (so he said, 599— 602) in pledge ; and to appeal to Chremes' sense of honour to pay it. This succeeds:
